    <style>
      html {
        font-size: 14px;
        height: 100vh;
      }
      body {
        font-family: Roboto, sans-serif;
        -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
        -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
        font-weight: 400;
        height: 100%;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        background-color: #e5e5e5;
        --mdc-theme-primary: #03a9f4;
        --mdc-theme-secondary: #03a9f4;
      }
      li {
        margin: 4px;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <my-layout>
      <style>
        a {
          color: var(--mdc-theme-primary);
        }
      </style>
        <img class="hero" src="/images/header.jpg" />
        <h1 class="card-header">
          Frequently Asked Questions
        </h1>
      <div class="card-content">
        <p><a href="/">&laquo; Back to My Home Assistant</a></p>
      </div>

      <div class="section-header">What does My Home Assistant solve?</div>
      <div class="card-content">
        <p>
          When explaining fuctionality or helping users, we often want to link them to a specific place in their instance. However, each Home Assistant instance lives somewhere else, and so we can't have a single place to link to. Until now.
        </p>
        <p>
          My Home Assistant allows users to store the URL of their instance so that the documentation can link the user directly to their instance. This data is stored in your browser and never leaves your computer.
        </p>
        <p>
          When the Home Assistant documentatino links you to a place in your instance, they will link you to My Home Assistant. My Home Assistant will then forward this to Home Assistant, which will open the right page.
        </p>
        <p>
          All this logic happens in your browser. At no point will any data leave your network. None of the supported redirects take any action. They either end up on a page that will provide you with information about your instance or help you start an action.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="section-header" id='supported-links'>Supported links</div>
      <div class="card-content">
        <p>
          The following links are supported:
        </p>
        {{ redirectList }}
      </div>

      <div class="section-header">XXXXXXXXX?</div>
      <div class="card-content">
        <p>
          My Home Assistant allows you to...
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="section-header">XXXXXXXXX?</div>
      <div class="card-content">
        <p>
          My Home Assistant allows you to...
        </p>
      </div>

    </my-layout>
    <script type="module" crossorigin="use-credentials">
      import "/{{ entrypoint }}";
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
